Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kirketon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from any of numerous places in Scotland so called, named as ‘church settlement’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"SIR","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ALEXANDER","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"BOZON,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: unexplained. This surname is very rare in France.","Hispanic (Dominican Republic; <b>Rozón</b>): variant of Galician and Spanish <b>Rosón</b>, possibly derived from Latin <i>rusus</i> ‘red’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Knight","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When SIR ALEXANDER BOZON, Knight De Kirketon was born in 1175, in Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Raduphus De Kirketon, was 20 and his mother, Lady Radulphus de Kirketon, was 25. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Dionysia de Sancto Paulo. He died in 1285, in his hometown, at the age of 110, and was buried in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1175–1285":"1175–1285","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1226–Male":"1226–Surnud","1239–1312":"1239–1312","–1303":"–1303","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1175":"1175","1285":"1285","1150":"1150","1239":"1239","abt 1226":"umbes 1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1226":"1226","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1155":"1155","about 1224":"umbes 1224","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Grey Friars,London,Middlesex,England":"London, Middlesex, England","Europe":"Europe","Kirketon Hoyland, Lincholnshire, England":"Saint Andrew, Nether Hoyland, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England":"Sibthorpe, Nottinghamshire, England","Staunton, Newark, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staunton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{